rogel.io.fopl.terms

Class Function

  • java.lang.Object
    • rogel.io.fopl.terms.Term
      • rogel.io.fopl.terms.Function
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Expression, Unifiable

    public final class Function
extends Term
    A Function is a mapping between a set of inputs and a set of outputs. In FOPL, the inputs and outputs are all Terms.
    Author:
    recardona

    • Constructor Detail

      • Function

        public Function(java.lang.String name,
        Term... terms)
        Constructs an n-ary Function with the given name. If the name is a String that did not already exist within the domain of discourse (i.e. was already defined as a Symbol), then a new Symbol is created and added to the domain of discourse. The arity of this Function depends on the number of Terms added.

        Note: A 0-ary Function is used to represent a constant symbol.

        Parameters:
        name - The name of the Function, not null.
        terms - The parameters to this Function, not null.

    • Method Detail

      • map

        public void map(Term value,
       Term firstArgument,
       Term... otherArguments)
        Defines a relation between the argument(s) and the value. This operation expands this Function's domain by the arguments, and the Function's co-domain by the value.

        For example, if x and y are Terms, and f is a Function, calling f.map(y, x) implies that subsequently calling f.evaluate(x) will return y.

        Parameters:
        value - A Term that will be in the co-domain of this Function mapped to the argument Terms.
        firstArgument - A Term that will be in the domain of this Function.
        otherArguments - a varargs of Terms that serve as additional arguments to this Function (used for defining multi-dimensional arguments).
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if this is a constant (i.e. a 0-ary function symbol).
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the number of arguments does not match the arity of this Function.
        See Also:
        evaluate(Term...)

      • evaluate

        public Term evaluate(Term... arguments)
        Attempts to evaluate the Function on the parameter argument.

        If this is a constant Function, the parameters are ignored, and the method returns this Function. Otherwise, this method returns the value mapped to the parameter arguments.

        Parameters:
        arguments - The arguments to this Function, not null.
        Returns:
        the value in this Function's co-domain given the argument, null if the argument does not form part of this Function's domain, or this object itself if this is a constant Function.
        See Also:
        map(Term, Term, Term...)

      • unify

        public Substitution unify(Unifiable unifiable,
                 Substitution substitution)
        Description copied from interface: Unifiable
        Attempts to find the Substitution that unifies (makes syntactically equivalent) this Unifiable Object with the parameter Unifiable Object, given an existing set of Substitutions. If no such Substitution exists, this method returns null.

        This method is commutative: calling u1.unify(u2, s) is equivalent to calling u2.unify(u1, s).

        Parameters:
        unifiable - the Object to attempt to unify with, not null.
        substitution - the existing set of Substitutions to work with, not null.
        Returns:
        a Substitution that unifies this Object with the parameter Unifiable, or null if no Substitution exists.

      • containsVariable

        public boolean containsVariable(Variable variable,
                       Substitution substitution)
        Description copied from interface: Unifiable
        Checks to see if this Unifiable expression contains the parameter Variable, given an existing set of Substitutions (which may involve the Variable to check for). This method accomplishes what is colloquially referred to as the "occurs check" during unification.
        Parameters:
        variable - the Variable to check for, not null.
        substitution - the existing set of Substitutions to work with, not null.
        Returns:
        true if this Unifiable Object contains the Variable, false otherwise.
